{"id":582510,"url":"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerry_Heller","text":"Gerald Elliot \"Jerry\" Heller (October 6, 1940 \u2013 September 2, 2016) was an American music manager and businessman. He was best known for managing West Coast rap supergroup and gangsta rap pioneers N.W.A and Eazy-E.\nEarly life.\nHeller was born in Cleveland, Ohio. He studied at the University of Southern California.\nCareer.\nHeller became famous in the 1960s and '70s, importing Elton John and Pink Floyd for their first major American tours, and representing Journey, Marvin Gaye, Van Morrison, War, Eric Burdon, Crosby Stills and Nash, Ike & Tina Turner, Creedence Clearwater Revival, Otis Redding, The Who, REO Speedwagon, Black Sabbath, Humble Pie, Styx, The Grass Roots and The Standells, among many others.\nIn the mid-1980s he worked with R&B and hip hop acts like Michel'le, World Class Wreckin' Cru, J.J. Fad, The D.O.C., Egyptian Lover and L.A. Dream Team.\nHeller played a role in the emergence of West Coast rap music when he managed Ruthless Records with Eazy-E and discovered, signed or managed the likes of N.W.A, The Black Eyed Peas, Above the Law, The D.O.C. and Bone Thugs-N-Harmony.\nDeath.\nHeller suffered from a heart attack while driving, resulting in an auto accident. He later died on September 2, 2016 in Thousand Oaks, California.","categories":[],"infobox_types":[],"annotations":[{"uri":"Music_manager","surface_form":"music manager","offset":83},{"uri":"West_Coast_hip_hop","surface_form":"West Coast rap","offset":145},{"uri":"Supergroup_(music)","surface_form":"supergroup","offset":160},{"uri":"Gangsta_rap","surface_form":"gangsta rap","offset":175},{"uri":"N.W.A","surface_form":"N.W.A","offset":196},{"uri":"Eazy-E","surface_form":"Eazy-E","offset":206},{"uri":"Cleveland%2C_Ohio","surface_form":"Cleveland, Ohio","offset":245},{"uri":"University_of_Southern_California","surface_form":"University of Southern California","offset":280},{"uri":"Elton_John","surface_form":"Elton John",